Rivers State Governor,  Nyesom Ezenwo Wike has declared that the country is sliding because judges are afraid to function in line with their oath of office. Speaking during a Courtesy Visit by the National Association of Women Judges,  South-South chapter on Tuesday, Governor Wike stressed that judges must always uphold the law. He said: “The problem with Nigeria today is people are afraid to say the truth. Judges are afraid.  They don’t want to be identified.  That is why the country is sliding down.” He regretted that Nigerians have allowed the country to degenerate so low. Governor Wike charged Judges not to allow themselves to be intimidated by any other arm of Government. AMCON takes over  Buba  Galadima’s assets in Abuja “Whether you like it or not, people will accuse you.  So, you must go ahead to do what is right. “Whatever you do, people will accuse you. You must understand the oath of office that you took,” he said. He said that the judiciary must defend itself from irrelevant accusations from other arms of Government. The Governor noted that  judiciary should not allow the Executive and Legislative Arms of the to muzzle  them. Earlier,  Chief Judge of Rivers State,  Justice Adama Iyaye-Laminkara said that the judges are in the state for a workshop organised by the United Nations Office of drugs and crime.  He said that the workshop will help the judges to administer Justice .. She said women judges from the Six South-South States  are in Port Harcourt for the conference.